===Health network===
{{See also|List of hospitals in Iran}}
[[Image:TUMS3.jpg|thumb|Shariati Hospital in [[Tehran]]|250px]]
Today the largest healthcare delivery network is owned and run by the [[Ministry of Health and Medical Education]] (MOHME) through its network of health establishments and medical schools in the country. MOHME is in charge of provision of healthcare services through its network, [[medical insurance]], [[medical education]], supervision and regulation of the [[healthcare system]] in the country, policymaking, production and distribution of pharmaceuticals, and research and development. Additionally, there are other parallel organisations such as Medical Services Insurance Organizations (MSIO) that have been established to act as a relief foundation as well as an [[insurance]] firm. Some hospitals, such as [[Mahak]] for children's cancer, are run by charitable foundations.

According to the last census that Statistical Centre of Iran undertook in 2003, Iran possesses 730 medical establishments (e.g. hospitals, clinics) with a total of 110,797 [[bed]]s, of which 488 (77,300 beds) are directly affiliated and run by the MOHME and 120 (11,301 beds) owned by the private sector and the rest belong to other organisations, such as the [[Social Security Organization (Iran)|Social Security Organization of Iran (SSO)]]. There were about seven [[nurse]]s and 17 hospital beds per 10,000 population.<ref name='Iran'/> 

An elaborate system of health network has been established which has ensured provision of [[Primary Health Centre|Primary Health Care]] (PHC) to the vast majority of public. However, access and [[availability]] of health care continues to be somewhat limited in [[Provinces of Iran|lesser developed provinces]] where the health indices are also lower as compared to national averages. The country is in an epidemiologic transition and faces double burden of the diseases. New emerging threats should also be considered. The [[Demography of Iran|demographic]] and epidemiological transition underway will have a significant effect on the pattern of morbidity and [[death|mortality]] in the near and distance future, especially as it affects the emergence of [[chronic (medicine)|chronic]] [[non-communicable disease]]s and the health problems of an [[aging]] population.

===Development===
{{See also|Science and technology in Iran|Economy of Iran}}
Although overall improvements have been achieved in all health areas since the 1979 revolution, the present challenging economic conditions of the country, combined with rapid advances in medical technology  and [[information technology]], individuals’ expectations, and the young [[Demographics of Iran|demographic]] of the population will undoubtedly challenge the sustainability of past improving trends. In this regard, Iran is implementing a reform that places [[preventive medicine]], the [[family doctor]] and the patient's electronic [[medical history]] at the center of Iran's health care system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Program/240811.html |title=PressTV - Family doctor in Iran |publisher=Presstv.ir |date= |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref> Moreover there is a considerable variation in the [[human development index]] and the human poverty index across different provinces in the country. Iran is the 19th country in medical research and is set to become the 10th within 10 years (2012).<ref>{{cite web|author= PressTV |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jqh702QhmzE |title=Iran´s significant advances in Biosimilar & Biotechnology Medicines |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

====Health tourism====
{{see also|Tourism in Iran}}
Iran is also among the 12 countries with biological medicines technology and can serve as a [[health tourism]] center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.com/detail/225321.html |title=Iran launches new biotechnological medicine line |publisher=PressTV |date=2012-02-06 |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref> 30,000 people come to Iran each year to receive medical treatment (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9010171549 |title=Fars News Agency :: Ahmadinejad Stresses Iran's Growing Medical Tourism Industry |publisher=English.farsnews.com |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

==Water and sanitation==
{{See also|Water supply and sanitation in Iran|List of reservoirs and dams in Iran}}
Iran has one of the highest percentages of population in the [[Middle East]] with access to safe [[drinking water]], with an esimated 92% of its people enjoying such access (nearly 100% in urban areas and about 80% in rural areas as of 2007).<ref>http://www.unicef.org/specialsession/about/sgreport-pdf/03_SafeDrinkingWater_D7341Insert_English.pdf</ref><ref>[http://www.wssinfo.org/pdf/country/IRN_wat.pdf Iran_islamic_rep_of_04.xls]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref>

There is a considerable shortfall in [[wastewater treatment]]; for example, in Tehran the majority of the population has no wastewater treatment, with raw [[sewage]] being injected directly into the [[groundwater]].<ref>[http://darwin.nap.edu/books/0309092930/html/217.html]</ref>  As the [[water crisis]] deepens with [[overpopulation|an expanding population]], this [[pollution]] of groundwater causes increasing health risks.

==Nutrition==
{{See also|Agriculture in Iran|Cuisine of Iran|List of countries by percentage of population suffering from undernourishment|Sport in Iran}}
[[Image:Percentage population undernourished world map.PNG|thumb|right|Percentage of national population suffering from [[malnutrition]], according to United Nations statistics.]]

Serious attention to the nutritional status of [[Iranian people]] has been made since [[Institute of Nutrition and Food Science of Iran]] (INFSI) was established by Dr. [[Habibollah Hedayat]] in 1961.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Despite the fact that Iran consists of an [[agrarian economy]]    {{Better source|date=June 2012}}, there is a high degree of [[malnutrition]] within the country. Approximately one fourth of all young children have [[stunted growth|stunted]] or wasted growth characteristics due to undernourishment;<ref>[http://www.fao.org/ag/agn/nutrition/ira-e.stm Nutrition country profiles: Iran summary]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> moreover, as an indicator of the poor [[food distribution]] capability, the percentage of undernourished children in [[village]]s is much higher. 

As an additional measure of [[public health]] and inefficient food distribution, about thirteen percent of the young people are classified as [[obese]], according to the same [[United Nations]] [[FAO]] sources. According to the government of Iran, about 60 percent of Iranians are [[overweight]] and 35 percent of women and 15 percent of men suffer from [[obesity]] in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1140.html |title=Health Minister: 60% of Iranians are overweight |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

''[[The Codex Commission of Food Stuff]]'', established in 2002 is in charge of setting and developing standards and quality and health regulations, related to the production of and trade in raw agricultural products and food stuffs, in accordance with the different global standards.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}} 

The [[soft drink]]s industry is valued at about $2 billion a year. Today, Iran produces about 3 billion litres of different types of soft drinks to address consumption of 46 litres per capita, and exports more than 12% of its production. Increased awareness with regards to the damages of carbonated drinks and sugar, and high levels of diabetes has created a move towards healthier products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atiehbahar.com/Resource.aspx?n=1000011 |title=Resources - Soft Drinks |publisher=Atieh Bahar |date=2008-10-20 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> {{undue-inline|reason=Is it related to the article?|date=June 2012}}

==Communicable diseases & addictions==
[[Immunization]] of children is accessible to most of the urban and rural population.<ref name='Iran'/>

===Cholera===
[[Cholera]] has been a persistent problem in Iran. In the 2005 epidemic which involved loss of lives, state television warned people not to eat vegetables or buy ice blocks on the streets.<ref>[http://www.iranian.ws/cgi-bin/iran_news/exec/view.cgi/3/8985 Iran [[cholera]] outbreak takes more life, mullahs' regime clueless - Persian Journal Iran news, Latest iran news Iranian newspaper women zan<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Salads were also banned in some restaurants. The 1998 epidemic involved considerably more cases and loss of life.

===HIV/AIDS===
{{See also|Prostitution in Iran
Increased drug use has driven up the incidence of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). In 2005 two-thirds of the official total of 9,800 HIV cases were attributed to drug use. Iran has established a national HIV treatment system, including 150 testing sites and a free needle exchange program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Iran.pdf |title=Country profile - US library of Congress |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

According to the [[United Nations]], [[AIDS]] has been increasing in Iran at a rapid rate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/Regions_Countries/Countries/Iran_Islamic_Republic_of.asp |title=Countries |publisher=Unaids.org |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> The major factor fuelling the epidemic until now has been injecting [[Recreational drug use|drug use]], while there is an increase in [[Sexually transmitted disease|sexual transmission]] of the disease. An estimated 14% of people who inject drugs countrywide were living with HIV in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://payvand.com/blog/blog/2010/12/05/graphs-iran-in-unaids-report-on-the-global-aids-epidemic-2010/ |title=Graphs: Iran in UNAIDS Report on the Global AIDS Epidemic 2010 |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> In 2009, men account for 93 percent of the HIV patients, and women comprise 7 percent of the infected population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/09/nov/1248.html |title=Surge in Iran's AIDS death rate |publisher=Payvand.com |date=2009-03-21 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

The rate of the epidemic in Iran is however still very low compared to international standards. Iran has a low prevalence of HIV infections with a rate of about 0.16 percent of the adult population (18,000 cases, officially) compared with 0.8 percent in North America (2008).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idUSTRE4AO44O20081125 | work=Reuters | title=Iran fights rise in sexually transmitted HIV | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> But according to the [[WHO]], as of the end of 2009, there are more than 100,000 AIDS sufferers in Iran (approximately 0.135% of the Iranian population).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=112423&sectionid=3510212 |title='Iran has 100,000 HIV-infected people' |publisher=Presstv.ir |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

===Illegal drugs===
{{See also|Opium in Iran|Central Bank of Iran#Anti-money laundering law|Crime in Iran|l2=Anti-money laundering law in Iran}}

[[Drug addiction]] constitutes a major health problem. Iran is situated along one of the main trafficking routes for cannabis, [[heroin]], [[opium]] and [[morphine]] produced in [[Afghanistan]], and designer drugs have also found their way into the local market in recent years. Iran ranks first worldwide in the [[List of countries by prevalence of opiates use|prevalence of opiate addiction]] with 2.8% of its population addicted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://payvand.com/blog/blog/2010/06/24/united-nations-world-drug-report-2010-and-iran/ |title=United Nations World Drug Report 2010 and Iran |publisher=Payvand.com |date=2010-06-24 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Initiation age for most Iranian addicts is their 20s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cancerjournal.net/article.asp?issn=0973-1482;year=2006;volume=2;issue=4;spage=182;epage=185;aulast=Tabei |title=Current substance use in patients with gastric cancer in Southern Iran Tabei SZ, Heydari ST, Mehrabani D, Shamsina SJ, Ahmadi J, Firouzi SM - J Can Res Ther |doi=10.4103/0973-1482.29828 |publisher=Cancerjournal.net |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>
Hundreds of drug production laboratories have been set up in [[Pakistan]] and Afghanistan.<ref name="iran-daily.com">[http://www.iran-daily.com/1388/3435/html/society.htm#s388974 ]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> Drug production in Afghanistan has multiplied by 40 times the previous output since the US-led invasion of the country in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=112760&sectionid=351020101 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Iran's police said in April 2009 that 7,700 tonnes of opium was produced in Afghanistan in 2008, of which 3000 tonnes entered Iran, adding that the force had managed to seize 1000 tonnes of the smuggled opium.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,21498,25451098-5005361,00.html?from=public_rss | work=AFP | title=Iran has 1.2 million drug addicts | date=2009-05-07}}</ref> Iran spent over 600 million dollars in just the last two years to dig canals, build barriers and install barbed wire to seal off the country’s crime-infested borders.<ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1387/3262/html/national.htm ]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> 

Iran discovers 3 tons of drugs daily.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/08/nov/1156.html |title=Iran discovers 3 tons of drugs daily: Police Chief |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/10/jun/1244.html |title=3 tons of drugs seized in Iran every day: police |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> In 2005, estimates of the number of drug addicts ranged from 2 to 4 million (1.2 million according to the Government).<ref>http://www.unodc.org/pdf/afg/afg_drug-situation_2002-10-01_1.pdf</ref> Reasons for addiction include lack of economic prospects among the youth and lack of freedom. 40% of prisoners in Iran have been convicted on drug related charges.<ref name="iran-daily.com"/> According to published figures, Iran has so far lost close to 3,500 police and security officers to the anti-drug campaign that annually costs the country almost $1 billion and inflicts an annual damage of about $8.5 billion on [[Economy of Iran|Iran's economy]].<ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1387/3275/html/national.htm ]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=117482&sectionid=351020102 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.ir |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

===Smoking===
{{See also|Taxation in Iran#Smuggling|l1=Smuggling in Iran}}
Iran has implemented a strict [[smoking ban]] in all public places (2007). According to the new law, [[smoking]] is prohibited in all public organizations, hotels, restaurants, tea houses and coffee shops. Also forbidden is the offering and smoking of ''[[ghalyun]]'', the traditional Persian [[waterpipe]], which is a must in Iranian [[tea house]]s. A smoking ban for all car drivers nationwide was implemented since March 2006, and although offenders could face fines, the ban was widely ignored by the drivers. Also selling tobacco products to anyone under 18 would result in confiscation of the vendor's tobacco products and a cash fine. Repeated violations would lead to high cash fines. 

About 20% of adult male and 4.5% of adult female population in the country smoke tobacco (12 million smokers according to some estimates).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-235/0812241246201050.htm |title=وب سایتهای ایرنا - Irna |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/09/jun/1006.html |title=25% of death in Iran caused by tobacco: Minister |publisher=Payvand.com |date=2009-05-31 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 60,000 Iranians die directly or indirectly due to smoking every year (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smokersclubinc.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1834 |title=Iran Compulsory Rules |publisher=The Smokers Club, Inc. |date=2007-12-22 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Smoking is responsible for 25% of death in the country.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> Approx. 54bn-60bn cigarettes are believed to be consumed annually in Iran.<ref name="New law"/> Around 2.7bn cigarettes are smuggled into Iran annually, according to officials from the state-owned [[Iranian Tobacco Company]] (ITC), on top of another 26.7bn which are imported legally (2008).<ref>{{Cite journal| first= | last=| coauthors=| contribution=IRAN: Food, Beverages and Tobacco Forecast| title=Economist Intelligence Unit| editor-first=| editor-last=| publisher=| place=| pages=| date=August 18, 2008| year=| id= | contribution-url=| format=| accessdate=2009-07-09| editors=| postscript= <!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. --> }}</ref> Imports of cigarettes, tobacco, cigars, cigarette paper, cigarette tips are subject to government monopoly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austrade.gov.au/australia/layout/0,,0_S2-1_CLNTXID0019-2_-3_PWB1151550-4_doingbusiness-5_-6_-7_,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061004192232/http://www.austrade.gov.au/australia/layout/0,,0_S2-1_CLNTXID0019-2_-3_PWB1151550-4_doingbusiness-5_-6_-7_,00.html |archivedate=2006-10-04 |title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2006-10-04 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Iranians spend more than $1.8 billion a year on tobacco.<ref name="New law"/> According to a 2010-law, smokers henceforth will not be appointed to [[Government of Iran|senior government jobs]].<ref name="New law">{{cite web|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1389/4/30/MainPaper/3732/Page/3/?NewsID=21253 |title=No. 3732 &#124; National &#124; Page 3 |publisher=Irandaily |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

===Air pollution===
{{See also|Environmental issues in Iran}}
The prevalence of respiratory diseases and cancers in Iran is increasing at a significant rate, also because of [[Tehran#Pollution|air pollution in Tehran]].<ref name="payvand.com"/> It is estimated that 5 million Iranian children suffer from asthma.<ref>[http://www.mehrnews.com/en/newsdetail.aspx?NewsID=1591366 ]{{dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref> The [[World Bank]] estimates losses inflicted on [[Economy of Iran|Iran’s economy]] as a result of deaths caused by air pollution at $640 million, which is equal to 5.1 trillion rials or 0.57 percent of [[GDP]].<ref>http://www.nitc.co.ir/iran-daily/1385/2798/html/index.htm</ref>

===Alcohol consumption===
{{See also|Alcohol in Iran|Beer in Iran}}
Prohibited in Iran because of the [[Sharia|Islamic law]], except for non-Muslims who can legally consume alcoholic beverages in private. Alcohol smuggling into Iran was estimated at nearly $1 billion in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.havocscope.com/regions-main/middle-east/iran/ |title=Iran - Havocscope Black Markets |publisher=Havocscope.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.havocscope.com/ranking/products/alphabetical/ |title=Havocscope Black Markets Listing - Havocscope Black Markets |publisher=Havocscope.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> More than 200,000 people in Iran are estimated to be involved in [[Rum-running|bootlegging]]. Many rely on what's made in people's basements or gardens in unsanitary conditions.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-iran-alcohol-20120707,0,5211937.story ]{{dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref>

== Family planning ==
{{See also|Family planning in Iran|Demography of Iran|Abortion in Iran|Women's rights in Iran}}

The Islamic Republic of Iran has a comprehensive and effective program of [[family planning]]. While Iran's population grew at a rate of more than 3% per year between 1956 and 1986, the growth rate began to decline in the late 1980s and early 1990s after the government initiated a major population control program. By 2007 the growth rate had declined to 0.7 percent per year, with a birth rate of 17 per 1,000 persons and a death rate of 6 per 1,000.<ref>[http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761567300_3/Iran.html MSN Encarta Encyclopedia entry on Iran - People and Society], [https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html#People CIA World factbook 2007]. [http://www.webcitation.org/5kwc3Hf9W Archived] 2009-10-31.</ref> Reports by the UN show birth control policies in Iran to be effective with the country topping the list of greatest fertility decreases. UN's Population Division of the Department of Economic and Social Affairs says that between 1975 and 1980, the total fertility number was 6.5. The projected level for Iran's 2005 to 2010 birth rate is fewer than two.<ref>[http://www.payvand.com/news/09/apr/1183.html Iran tops world in birth control], payvand.com 04/17/09, accessdate = 2010-03-23</ref><ref name="abcnews.go.com">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iran-urges-baby-boom-16881781 |title=International News &#124; World News - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-04-03 |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref> As at 2012, more than half of Iran's population is under 35 years old. Authorities are now slashing its birth-control programs in an attempt to avoid an [[demography of Iran|aging demographic]] similar to many Western countries that are struggling to keep up with state medical and [[Social Security Organization (Iran)|social security costs]].<ref name="abcnews.go.com"/>

==Leading causes of mortality==
{{See also|Transport in Iran#Road accidents|l1=Road accidents in Iran}}

In the early 2000s the main natural causes of death have been [[cardiovascular]] disease and [[cancer]].

According to [[Ministry of Health and Medical Education]], in 2003, 41% of total deaths were due to diseases of the circulatory system. [[Myocardial infarction]] as the cause of 25% of deaths was the leading cause of mortality among the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranpharmaceutical.com/iran-health-indicators-and-health-care-system.html |title=Iran Health Indicators and Health Care System |publisher=Iranpharmaceutical.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

[[Substance dependence|Addiction]] is the fourth major cause of death in Iran following [[Transport in Iran#Road accidents|road accidents]], [[heart disease]] and [[Major depressive disorder|depression]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-234/0810278680174556.htm |title=وب سایتهای ایرنا - Irna |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

From 2001 to 2010, over 438,000 Iranians have died from "unnatural deaths" such as electric shocks, gas poisoning, and drug intoxication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/aug/1075.html |title=Over 0.4 million lost lives in Iran in 10 years due to accidents |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref>

==Pharmaceuticals==

The pharmaceutical industry in Iran began in its modern form in 1920 when the [[Pasteur Institute]] was founded. Iran has a well-developed [[pharmaceutical]] production capability, however, the country still relies on imports for raw materials and many specialized drugs. The standards regarding pharmaceutical products in Iran are determined and modified by the ''Pharmacopeia Council''.

Iran’s [[Ministry of Health and Medical Education]] (MOHME) has a mission to provide access to sufficient quantities of safe, effective and high quality medicines that are affordable for the entire population. Since the 1979 revolution, Iran has adopted a full generic-based [[National Drug Policy]] (NDP), with local production of [[essential drugs]] and [[vaccines]] as one of the main goals.<ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1385/2773/html/economy.htm Iran-Daily: Biggest Pharmaceutical Plant to Open Soon]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref>

Although over 85 percent of the population use an insurance system to reimburse their drug expenses, the government heavily subsidizes pharmaceutical production/importation in order to increase affordability of medicines, which tends also to increase overconsumption, overprescription and misuse of drugs, such as [[antibiotics#Antibiotic resistance|antibiotics]]. The regulatory environment of the country is rather strict on the import of drugs and pharmaceuticals towards companies that intend to enter into the market for the first time. The Ministry of Health and Medical Education is the main stakeholder of pharmaceutical affairs in the country.

===Market===
{{see also|Iranian targeted subsidy plan}}
In 2006, 55 [[List of Iranian companies#Pharmaceuticals|pharmaceutical companies]] in Iran produce more than 96 percent (quantitatively) of medicines on the market, worth $1.2 billion annually.<ref>[http://iran-daily.com/1386/2880/html/national.htm Iran Daily - National - 07/01/07]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> Iran’s pharmaceutical market is estimated to be worth $1.87 billion (2008), $2.31 billion (2009) and $3.65bn by 2013 (projected).<ref name="payvand.com"/><ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1387/3249/html/economy.htm ]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref><ref name=companiesandmarket/>
The drug market in Iran is heavily in favour of [[generic drug|generic medicines]], which contributed US$1.23bn to the total in 2009, with patented drugs at US$817mn and [[Over-the-counter drug|OTC]] medicines at US$262mn.<ref name=companiesandmarket>{{cite web|author=Greg Palast |url=http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=107645&catid=1015 |title=Pharmaceuticals: Afghan Ufficiale: La NATO Airstrike Uccide 14 |publisher=OfficialWire |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

The market share of local production (value-wise) has declined from 85.2% to 63.4% over the past 8 (Iranian) years (2009). In this period the value of importation has jumped from 14.8% to 36.6%.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasoohi |first=Sasan |url=http://iran-pharma.blogspot.com/2008_12_10_archive.html |title=Iran Pharma: 12/10/08 |publisher=Iran-pharma.blogspot.com |date=2008-12-10 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> The government imposes 90% tariff on the import of drugs. In 2009, 1.8 million units of pharmaceutical products worth $1.2 billion were imported into Iran.<ref name="turquoisepartners.com">http://www.turquoisepartners.com/iraninvestment/IIM-Dec10.pdf</ref>

====Products====
{{See also|Science and technology in Iran}}

Iran has produced a wide range of pharmaceuticals drugs for the treatment of cancer, diabetes, infection and depression.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iran-daily.com/1389/1/14/MainPaper/3644/Page/8/?NewsID=12884 |title=No. 3644 &#124; Science &#124; Page 8 |publisher=Irandaily |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

The Islamic Republic of Iran is the first country in the East Mediterranean region which has the technical and scientific capability to export vaccines to various world countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zawya.com/Story.cfm/sidZAWYA20100506105410/Iran%20joins%20world%20vaccine%20producers%20 |title=Iran joins world vaccine producers |publisher=Zawya |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=126040&sectionid=3510210 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Iran will gain self-sufficiency in vaccine production by 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jan/1017.html |title=Iran to gain self-sufficiency in vaccine production |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

The new drugs launched in Iran for the treatment of [[Multiple sclerosis|MS]] include an [[interferon beta]]-1b by [[CinnaGen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1389/8/24/MainPaper/3827/Page/1/index.htm# |title=No. 3827 &#124; Front page &#124; Page 1 |publisher=Irandaily |date=2010-11-15 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> [[Gamma Immunex]] (recombinant interferon beta 1), [[Pegaferon]] (recombinant [[pegylated]] interferon ([[PEG-IFN]])) and regenerative human factor VIII are among other [[recombinant]]-based medication made in Iran.<ref name="presstv.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/155433.html |title=Iran to produce 8 recombinant drugs |publisher=PressTV |date=2010-12-14 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> [[List of Iranian scientists|Iranian researchers]] are going to produce eight new recombinant drugs by March 2011.<ref name="presstv.com"/> Iran mass produces MS drug [[Ziferon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/143010.html |title=Iran mass produces MS drug Ziferon |publisher=PressTV |date=2010-09-18 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> A generic version of [[fingolimod]] by [[Novartis]] has been launched as well as a biosimilar version of EMD [[Serono]]′s [[Rebif]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=90441&sectionid=3510210 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

Iranian researchers have developed 41 types of anti-cancer medications, overcoming the need for importing pricey [[cancer drug]]s from abroad (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=120211&sectionid=3510210 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/apr/1109.html |title=Iranian researchers produce new medicine for cancer treatment |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/12/jan/1301.html |title=Iranian scientists produce new drugs |publisher=Payvand.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref> 12 countries in the world produce [[bio-tech]] drugs; Iran is one of them.<ref>ttp://presstv.com/detail/222690.html</ref> There are also 24 additional [[biosimilar]] drugs which Iran plans to bring into production by end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/222098.html |title=PressTV - Iran making advancements In biosimilar medicines |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=2012-01-20 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Iran plans to become self-sufficient in [[biotech]] medicines production within 4 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=115704&sectionid=3510210 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref>

=====Innovation=====
{{See also|Science in Iran#Science in modern Iran|l1=Science and technology in Iran}}
In recent years several drugmakers are gradually developing the ability to innovate, away from [[generic drugs]] production itself.<ref name=companiesandmarket/> Depending on sources between 2,000 and 7,500 [[plant]] species are grown in Iran; only 100-300 of which are being used in [[pharmaceutical]] industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mehrnews.com/en/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=442498 |title=Iran’s share of worldwide medicinal plant trade barely 2% |publisher=Mehrnews.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web|url=http://iran-daily.com/1388/12/15/MainPaper/3632/Page/4/Index.htm |title=No. 3632 &#124; Domestic Economy &#124; Page 4 |publisher=Irandaily |date= |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> Iran has 80 percent of the world medicinal herbs. Due to lack of required technology, they are exported raw and in limited quantities to foreign markets.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>

===Pharmaceutical companies===
{{See also|List of Iranian companies}}
There are 92 companies in Iran that are active in the pharmaceutical industry.<ref name="turquoisepartners.com"/>  The ''Social Security Investment Co. (SSIC)'', Iran's largest holding company, which is affiliated to the [[Ministry of Welfare and Social Security (Iran)|Ministry of Welfare]], presently owns and controls 22 pharmaceutical manufacturing companies and possesses a 40% share of total pharmaceutical production in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atiehbahar.com/Resource.aspx?n=1000012 |title=Resources - Pharmaceuticals |publisher=Atieh Bahar |date=2008-10-20 |accessdate=2012-02-05}}</ref> 

The leading pharmaceuticals company is [[Darou Pakhsh]], which is majority-owned by the [[Social Security Organization (Iran)|Social Security Organization]]. The company manufactures, distributes, imports and exports finished products and pharmaceutical raw materials. [[Darou Pakhsh]] has an annual turnover of US$400m and claims to have the largest research and development operation of any Iranian drug firm. The company formed a [[plasmapheresis]] joint venture with a German medical firm, Biotest AG, in early 2004.<ref name='Iran'/> As of 2010, 50% of raw materials and chemicals used in the drug manufacturing sector are imported.<ref>http://www.turquoisepartners.com/iraninvestment/IIM-Jun10.pdf</ref>

Iranian pharmaceutical manufacturers are disadvantaged by the government′s poor [[Iran and copyright issues|intellectual property protection regime]] and because of lack of [[Foreign Direct Investment in Iran|foreign direct investment]].<ref name="payvand.com"/>

